				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="round-up">
<div class="ru-top-story">
<h6 class="kicker"></h6>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"> BIG BREAKS FOR BANKS <span class="divider">&nbsp;|&nbsp;</span></span><!-- end .title --> If, as expected, two banking giants â Credit Suisse and BNP Paribas â plead guilty to criminal charges in the next few weeks, they will probably pay large fines and officially be felons, <b><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/05/16/business/banks-that-are-criminals-remain-in-business.html?ref=business">Floyd Norris writes in the High &#038; Low Finance column</a></b>. But, he asks, does it matter that these will be criminal, not civil, punishments? The issue is not that banks may be âtoo big to jail,â but that, big or small, banks and other corporations are &#8220;<b>too inanimate to jail</b>,â Mr. Norris writes.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Companies cannot be sent to prison</b>, but they can still face the death penalty, which is why there has been an aggressive effort leading up to the expected criminal charges to assure that the banks will stay in business after they plead guilty. âTo put it another way, the Justice Department has gone to great lengths to guarantee that convicted banks <b>will not be treated as criminals</b>,â Mr. Norris writes. âIn being treated that way, the banks will receive the same breaks other banks have come to expect when they are caught violating rules or laws.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Laws that often prohibit violators</b> from taking part in certain business or receiving privileges granted to law-abiding companies are routinely waived as part of settlements with the Securities and Exchange Commission and other government agencies. For its part, the S.E.C. has not appeared eager to publicize the waivers.<br />
Mr. Norris writes: âWaivers may be practically necessary to settle cases, and they may justly avoid excessive punishments that would reduce competition in banking. But at least <b>they deserve more sunlight than they now receive</b>.â</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">PINTEREST RAISES MORE MONEY <span class="divider">&nbsp;|&nbsp;</span></span><!-- end .title --> Pinterest said on Thursday that it had raised $200 million in a new round of fund-raising, at a valuation of $5 billion, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/05/15/pinterest-raises-more-money-fetching-a-valuation-of-5-billion">Michael J. de la Merced writes in DealBook</a></b>. At that level, the social network has joined the ranks of the start-up superstars. <b>The money will come from existing investors</b>, including SV Angel and Andreessen Horowitz.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Pinterestâs latest fund-raising round</b> comes only six months after the social network raised $225 million at a $3.8 billion valuation. In total, Pinterest has raised $764 million in six rounds of financing.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"> CHIPOTLE CHIEFSâ PAY PLAN REJECTED <span class="divider">&nbsp;|&nbsp;</span></span><!-- end .title --> Investors in Chipotle Mexican Grill voted overwhelmingly on Thursday against the companyâs executive compensation plans, sending a strong rebuke to a company that had awarded more than $300 million to its co-chief executives in recent years, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/05/15/chipotle-investors-vote-against-executive-pay">DealBookâs David Gelles writes</a></b>. Last year, Chipotle paid its founder and co-chief executive, Steve Ells, $25.1 million in cash and stock. It paid Montgomery F. Moran, the companyâs other co-chief executive, $24.4 million.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>More than 75 percent of investors</b> voted against Chipotleâs say-on-pay measure, which asked investors to ratify a compensation plan that would continue such payments over the next few years. That was the highest vote against any say-on-pay measure among the countryâs largest 3,000 companies this year. Though the vote is nonbinding, Chipotle said it was taking investor sentiment into consideration. </p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">ON THE AGENDA <span class="divider">&nbsp;|&nbsp;</span></span><!-- end .title --> Monthly data on <b>housing starts</b> is out at 8:30 a.m. The Thomson Reuters/University of Michigan <b>consumer sentiment index</b> for May is out at 9:55 a.m. <b>James B. Bullard</b>, the president of the St. Louis Fed, speaks on the economy and monetary policy at 11:50 a.m. in Little Rock. Ark. <b>Goldman Sachs</b> holds its annual meeting of shareholders in Irving, Tex. at 9:30 a.m. local time. The quest for horse racingâs Triple Crown continues on Saturday with the <b>Preakness Stakes</b>.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"> DETROITâS BANKRUPTCY DEADLINE IN PERIL <span class="divider">&nbsp;|&nbsp;</span></span><!-- end .title --> Judge Steven Rhodes, the federal judge handling Detroitâs bankruptcy, indicated on Thursday that he may not be able to rule in the case by the Sept. 30 deadline, raising questions about whether Detroit can exit bankruptcy before the end of its emergency managerâs term, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/05/15/detroit-bankruptcy-deadline-may-be-missed-imperiling-state-funds">Mary Williams Walsh writes in DealBook</a></b>. If he does not approve Detroitâs bankruptcy plan by the end of September, it could also affect state allocations for the city.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>During the hearing</b>, Judge Rhodes âseemed to be alluding to the thick stack of objections to Detroitâs bankruptcy plan that piled up in the courthouse this week in response to a deadline,â Ms. Walsh writes. Many of the objections complain that Detroit is improperly proposing to treat its pensioners more favorably than its investors. Some cite the so-called grand bargain, which proposed to use the cityâs famous art collection to raise $816 million for retireesâ pensions. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Detroitâs plan of debt adjustment</b>, which lays out the terms it wants to use to settle its various debts, is scheduled to go to trial in July, when Judge Rhodes will have to decide how to handle any remaining objections. Bankruptcy experts said it would be difficult, though not impossible, to negotiate settlements to so many disputes before the confirmation hearing.</p>
</div>
